      "writtenOn": "2020-11-05T17:27:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why isn\u0027t SkTArray just SkSTArray with a zero sized storage?",
      "revId": "b8a6fcb45e672d2866810aa1b7d6ce73fad34956",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "18a675ad_3356d9c8",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-05T18:10:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One of the use cases that causes some strange abstraction-barrier-crossing implementation choices is to have a common base type for all SkSTArray and SkTArray, to be able to work with an SkTArray* and not care whether it points to an SkTArray per se or to SkSTArray\u003c10\u003e, SkSTArray\u003c1\u003e, etc.\n\nI\u0027m not exactly sure I know enough of how that use case is used today to know whether it\u0027s something we really need to preserve, but if not, I agree there\u0027s a lot of rearranging here to make things behave a bit more normally.  Removing the inheritance there is the first step and should show all the places that\u0027d need rethinking.",
      "parentUuid": "f4461003_775a2b72",
      "revId": "b8a6fcb45e672d2866810aa1b7d6ce73fad34956",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "749c6c65_e9e5425a",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-05T19:38:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "At one point I did do an experiment with a kind-of fused hybrid SkTArray + SkSTArray class called SkInlinedVector. Combining the classes allowed me to save memory by unioning `fStorage` on top of the space used by `fItemArray/fReserved/fAllocCount`, since in \"stack mode\" we don\u0027t need these things. This gave us 12 extra bytes when in stack mode \"for free.\" But it\u0027s a challenge to do this without adding complexity to very common paths like operator[]. I never got it to a point where I felt like it was ready to be full no-compromise replacement for SkTArray and eventually I moved on from the idea. But the concept has definitely got potential! I\u0027m glad to see someone else independently arrive there.",
      "parentUuid": "18a675ad_3356d9c8",
      "revId": "b8a6fcb45e672d2866810aa1b7d6ce73fad34956",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    }
